She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you reading old memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's almost time."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only daughter in the family, which was otherwise composed only of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had mentioned her non-binaryity, it was as if the world had changed too. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
She also had to remain in the service of the princess, but that wasn't too bad, because it made her an friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?", Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was just a few days away. Kari nodded, a sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" Ivory asked, recalling what she had said last time.
No, Kari replied bluntly. Ivory knew that was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but she remembered the indignation of the servants and the inhabitants. She had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Okay... what do you want to do?", Ivory asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Ivory a piece of paper. But when Ivory glanced at it...
15 cm x 15 cm Paint-by-Numbers Kit
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find those things for you?" Ivory asked, turning to the silent princess who was frantically typing, shaking her curls back and forth. "Yes?" She giggled lightly seeing the normally reserved princess get passionate about something. This was the first time she asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. Later?" Ivory proposed, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari acquiesced and retreated into her memories by wrapping herself in her thick blanket again.
She left the room with relief. The princess was finally leaving her comfort zone by asking for things that were not her domain, such as paint.
She backtracked through the corridors, trying not to listen to the murmurs of the servants.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Ivory covered her ears, as trying to ignore it didn't work. She headed towards the royal painter's room, which was located on the east side, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was as intricate as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, which, according to legend, created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved history.
Ivory opened the door, expecting to see a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, scattered pencils and papers, and easels covering every inch of the wall. Surprisingly, she saw none of that. The room was clean, and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool in front of it. On the stool, Prince Aquilo was sitting, getting his portrait painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! Are you here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Pardon, little prince," she replied, partly ignoring him, to search for the objects that her silent friend wanted. "I'm just here to get supplies."
"Ah, the girl will leave very soon?" Aquilo asked, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and had placed them in a box she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about that, however. "Oh, my dear, you know it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," she said, suddenly feeling uneasy, due to the prince's words, which reminded her of all the harm people said about her gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared at the door immediately, ignoring the painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" he scolded.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he wants to live." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned towards Ivory. "What do you say to a romantic meeting?" Ivory shivered. Yes, she had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, who was also the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what 'no' means?" she asked, pushing the prince out of her way.
"Oh no," Aquilo replied with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what that word means.
Ivory rolled his eyes. "Why want a romantic meeting with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact". He threw his hair back, making it fly in the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I am the palace threat." She wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo put his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
